---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import NewsletterForm from '../components/NewsletterForm.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Us"
  description="Meet the Sails & Trails family — a multi-generational crew of cruise lovers, hikers, and adventure seekers."
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-16">
    <p class="text-ocean-600 font-semibold text-sm uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">The crew</p>
    <h1 class="font-serif text-4xl font-semibold mb-8">About Sails &amp; Trails</h1>

    <div class="prose prose-lg prose-slate max-w-none prose-headings:font-serif">

      <h2>Hi, I'm Bailey</h2>
      <p>
        By day I'm a cloud architect — which means I spend a lot of time thinking about
        infrastructure, redundancy, and what happens when things go sideways.
        It turns out this is surprisingly good training for traveling with young children.
      </p>
      <p>
        I started this site because we kept having these incredible travel experiences and I
        couldn't find anyone writing about them honestly — the logistics, the details, the
        stuff that actually matters when you're wrangling a 3-year-old on a gangway.
        So I decided to write it myself.
      </p>
      <p>
        I travel with my husband, our daughter (5) and son (3), and an extended family that has
        somehow become one of the most adventure-prone groups of people I've ever met.
      </p>

      <h2>The Extended Crew</h2>
      <p>
        Most of our big trips happen because of <strong>Barbara</strong> — my mother-in-law,
        co-author of this site, and the person who books the Disney concierge suites AND
        dehydrates her own meals for PCT segments. She contains multitudes.
        Her husband joins us on the cruises and matches her energy completely.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're also regularly joined by two brothers-in-law, one of whom adventured to Antarctica
        with his wife before their daughter was born (she's 1 now and already has a better
        passport stamp collection than most adults).
      </p>

      <h2>What we write about</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Cruises</strong> — mostly Disney Cruise Line right now, with a long history of
        Royal Caribbean before the kids arrived. We write about the real experience: what concierge
        actually gets you, how to survive sea days with toddlers, what to do in port when half
        your group needs nap time.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Trails</strong> — Barbara covers the serious stuff (Tour du Mont Blanc, New Zealand's
        Great Walks, the PCT). We'll be writing about family camping and hiking as our kids' legs
        get longer and their complaints per mile decrease.
      </p>

      <h2>The bigger goal</h2>
      <p>
        We'd love for this to grow into something that cruise lines and travel companies notice —
        not because we're influencers, but because we're a real family who books real trips and
        writes about them with real detail. If you're a cruise line reading this: hi. We'd love to talk.
      </p>

      <h2>A note on details</h2>
      <p>
        I am constitutionally incapable of giving vague advice. If I tell you something is worth
        doing, I'll tell you exactly why, what it costs, how to book it, and what could go wrong.
        You've been warned.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <NewsletterForm />
</BaseLayout>
